{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e0199609-8c2a-433c-a476-2f447e0b3799","content":"Here's what you need:\n\n**Environment variables** for the container:\n\n```yaml\nenv:\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump\n    value: \"1\"\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType\n    value: \"4\"                          # Full dump (use \"2\" for Heap if space-constrained)\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName\n    value: \"/dumps/core.%p.%t\"          # %p=PID, %t=timestamp\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath\n    value: \"/opt/tools/createdump\"      # Required for NativeAOT — runtime doesn't bundle it\n```\n\n**Pod spec changes** — volume, security context, and resource limit:\n\n```yaml\nspec:\n  containers:\n    - name: my-app\n      securityContext:\n        capabilities:\n          add: [\"SYS_PTRACE\"]           # createdump needs ptrace access\n      volumeMounts:\n        - name: crash-dumps\n          mountPath: /dumps\n  volumes:\n    - name: crash-dumps\n      emptyDir:\n        sizeLimit: 2Gi                  # tune to your process memory size\n```\n\n**Key notes:**\n\n- **`SYS_PTRACE`** is required — without it `createdump` silently fails.\n- **`DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath`** is mandatory for NativeAOT since the runtime doesn't ship with `createdump` embedded.\n- `emptyDir` is fine for transient collection; switch to a **PVC** if you need dumps to survive pod restarts.\n- Dump type `4` (Full) captures everything but can be large. Use `2` (Heap) for a smaller dump that still includes managed heap data.\n\nTo retrieve dumps from a crashed (but not yet evicted) pod:\n\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/dumps/ ./local-dumps/ -c my-app\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2f983712-c81a-4901-8a7a-9837a5aaa848","outputTokens":482,"requestId":"6813:1E80:CA722E:E8D938:69FD41F3"},"id":"35870d8e-ae46-4b58-a52e-3d248df332cd","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:53:02.155Z","parentId":"816be184-c2eb-49c7-8c5a-74a171f0de21"}
